 Have you heard about how Hawking applied Quantum mechanics to general relativity regarding black hole singularities? (Pournelle reported on a presentation Hawking gave in the US called &quot;The Breakdown of Physics in the region of Space-Time singularities&quot; The title flashed on a screen, and was quickly replaced with the word &quot;Physics&quot; crossed out, and the word &quot;Physicists&quot; replacing it...<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> )<br>
He had already established that they &quot;evaporate&quot;, and small ones might not actually last very long (A shame, because there are all sorts of fun things you can do with small singularities). Blackholes may have an escape speed at or above &quot;C&quot;, but they do evaporate and emit stuff (and I don't pretend to follow the math).<br>
 What he said now, was that not only do they emit energy &amp; particles, but they must emit energy &amp; matter <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> in any &amp; all possible forms</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, if gven enough time (and there's every reason to believe that massive singularities were created in the early dense periods immediately after the 'Big Bang', and it's simple to prove that many should have been formed since then).<br>
 He said it will take a given singularity a long time to emit one of us, but given a long enough time, they might... and anything unimaginable else. There's no possibility of predicting when or what.<br>
 Hawking said<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Not only does god play dice with the universe, he sometimes throws them where even he cannot see them.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
