 <p>Life is too precious to waste on such things as racism, sexism, and difference of creed. Because humanity is humanity and we are all under one roof.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uarkuunaves.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ArkuunAves</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 114<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/21/02 11:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=286.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Coercion doesn't imply &quot;force&quot;</span><hr size=1> Banning the pledge would be a terrible idea.  That would actually be in violation of the Bill of Rights.  Now, if you want to get rid of laws requiring the Pledge to have a place in procedings....eh, that's yer own thing, but I personally still believe it is foolish.<br>
<br>
The only thing required is that one stands for the Pledge.  There is no law requiring the recitation of it.<br>
<br>
And as to having to stand for the pledge...I consider it an honor rendered to the flag, which thousands upon thousands of Americans have laid their lives down over history to first bring about and then to defend.<br>
<br>
I'd love to see a poll among the military of their feelings on this, even non-Christians.  These people know better than anyone else what the flag means. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 222<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/23/02 2:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=286.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   What are we honoring?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; I consider it an honor rendered to the flag, which thousands<br>
upon thousands of Americans have laid their lives down over<br>
history to first bring about and then to defend.<br>
&gt;<br>
&gt; I'd love to see a poll among the military of their feelings on this,<br>
even non-Christians. These people know better than anyone else<br>
what the flag means.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I took the oath &quot;... to defend the constitution of the United States, against all enemies...&quot;<br>
 Not the flag; not the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> symbol</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> which doesn't itself say anything about what we believe or are defending.<br>
The quote I added below says a lot about the flag, but that's not what's really being defended by the soldier (From a West Point graduation address).<br>
It pretty well lays down what I was thinking when I signed on the dotted line. I didn't sign up to defend the politicians of the moment, or the image on the TV of the red, white &amp; blue waving in the breeze.<br>
<br>
 In one of his last books (&quot;Demon Haunted World&quot; I think), Carl Sagan wrote that it would be better for us all if the pledge to the flag was abandoned, in favor of something more like a recognition of the ideals behind the union, as embodied in the Constitution. Some thing more like what judges and soldiers do when they take the oath. Every citizen should have to at least say this out loud, even if they're not signing a contract to take specific actions.<br>
 Pledging to the flag is like swearing blind obedience to follow the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> symbol</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, wherever it leads. <br>
<br>
 &quot;My country right or wrong&quot; is dead wrong. Not at all what Americans should be saying. Anbody you hear mouthing that stupid vacuous phrase should be stripped of voting rights (and high school graduation and anything with more responsibilities than grade school reading badge) and sent to basic citizenship classes.<br>
It should say &quot;When right, to be kept right. When wrong, to be put right&quot;.<br>
<br>
(Note that this sentiment is not directly why I was favorable to what the 9th circ. court decided. Separation is a different topic. I agreed  with taking the &quot;under Dog&quot; out of the pledge, I'm also in favor of abandoning the pledge, for more of a thinking-creatures' recognition of what being American means -or should mean.)<br>
<br>
<br>
It is the soldier, not the reporter<br>
Who has given us freedom of the press<br>
It is the soldier, not the clergyman<br>
Who has given us freedom of religion<br>
It is the soldier, not the poet<br>
Who has given us freedom of speech<br>
It is the soldier, not the campus organizer<br>
Who has given us freedom to demonstrate<br>
It is the soldier<br>
Who follows the flag into battle<br>
Who defends the flag<br>
And whose coffin is draped by the flag <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0> at: 9/23/02 3:44:04 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uarkuunaves.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ArkuunAves</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 119<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/24/02 8:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=286.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What are we honoring?</span><hr size=1> If you've taken the oath &quot;...to defend my country against all enemies, both foreign and domestic...&quot;  then you more than anyone should realize the importance of The Colors.<br>
<br>
My apologies, but I fail to see how you could <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> not</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> see the importance, if you have to salute the flag every time it's going up or coming down when in uniform, and stand at attention in the direction of the bugle call even if you're in civvies and can't see where the flag is.<br>
<br>
How many stroies are there of soldiers <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> dying</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to secure the flag, or take it down as they leave a post?<br>
<br>
Like it or not, symbolism is a very powerful thing.  The flag itself is the symbol of our ideals of freedom and justice, and also a reminder of many wars or blood and courage that have been waged in defense of our liberties.<br>
<br>
I whole-heartedly agree that the attitude of this country should be to keep right what is right and fix what isn't.  I do believe, however, that having the line &quot;...under God&quot; in a Pledge of Allegiance is not out of line.  In fact, it is perfectly <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> in</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> line with the very end of the service oaths and legal oaths which state &quot;...So help me God.&quot;  It is in line with US money stating &quot;In God We Trust&quot;.  The classic form of the code for US soldiers was &quot;God, Duty, Honor, Country&quot;, with God being before anything else.<br>
<br>
<br>
The point of a separation of church and state was that there should be no state-sanctioned and state-<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> required</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> religion.  It was <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> not</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> a call for leaving religion out of government.  Nearly all of our Founding Fathers were religious themselves, of various sects, and would be today radically opposed to such a concept of getting religion out of givernment entirely.<br>
<br>
I think it's important that no religion be forced upon citizens by government, and that there be no penalty for being of a different religion that someone in government.  That leaves open many possibilities,tho.<br>
<br>
If you're atheist, then what difference does it make if you say &quot;....under God&quot;?  You're simply repeating words that have no meaning to you,since you believe there is no God.<br>
<br>
If you're agnostic, then I don't see how it would bother you...you're not really sure if God exists anyway. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 225<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/24/02 9:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=286.topic&index=25>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What are we honoring?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; The point of a separation of church and state was<br>
that there should be no state-sanctioned and state-<br>
required religion. It was not a call for leaving religion<br>
out of government. Nearly all of our Founding Fathers<br>
were religious themselves, of various sects, and would<br>
be today radically opposed to such a concept of getting<br>
religion out of givernment entirely.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 I don't pretend to know their minds so well. How long have you studied their life's works and all their writings -letters, essays, articles, books, etc?<br>
 I do know that they and the citizens of the original states were of all sorts of religions. In some states, if you weren't Catholic, then you weren't dirt. In others, Catholicism was outlawed. Other differences abounded.<br>
<br>
The point of what the 9th circ court did, was to protect those who don't have the word &quot;Dog&quot; as an important part of their faith. How would you feel if the thoughtlessly enacted laws (not to say callous, but thoughtless as in not considered well enough) forced you or your kids to mouth words not in keeping with your spiritual views? &quot;It's just words...&quot; never mind that it refers to something that your people fought wars to separate themselves from or goes against the very grain of what you choose to believe...<br>
<br>
 And when I took that oath, I asked the officer giving the oath to the group I was part of, what should I do at that part? He boggled for a moment (new at this) and said to keep the solemnity and deadly seriousness of the oath in mind and keep silent while others said that part, if I wanted to.<br>
 I told him that I realised the significance of the oath, and I wasn't being frivolous -that simply saying &quot;So help me God&quot; like everybody else, just out of convenience, to not rock the boat <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> would have been frivolous</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. (I remembered the seriousness, but I copied George Burns at the last instant...)<br>
 &quot;So help me Dog&quot; wouldn't hold a tea cup's meaning to me.<br>
 Don't know what I'll do if I ever have to testify in court. Anybody know what they do in cases like that?<br>
<br>
 When they asked me what to put on my dogtags for religious preference, I said none. They put down &quot;no rel pref&quot; when I would have actually preferred &quot;none&quot;.<br>
They say that there are no atheists in the trenches. If somebody is satisfied with their lives in all ways, until they see people being blown apart left &amp; right, and suddenly realise that it'll happen to them, and what'll happen to their &quot;soul&quot; if there is a god, and then convert, why should god take them in? He's so forgiving that he'll accept fealty out of hypocrisy?<br>
<br>
Agnostics are so misunderstood. <br>
 I'm somewhere between/amongst atheism/agnosticism/pantheism.<br>
<br>
 The trials of agnosticism, according to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.serve.com/bonzai/monty/classics/TheChurchBells">Python</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Well I've always said, There's nothing an agnostic can't do if he really doesn't know whether he believes in anything or not.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
 This <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.serve.com/bonzai/monty/songs/AllThingsDullandUgly">bit</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> might go for a pantheist...<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> (singing)<br>
All things dull and ug-ly,<br>
All creatures, short and squat,<br>
All things rude and na-sty,<br>
The Lord God made the lot.<br>
 <br>
Each little snake that poisons,<br>
Each little wasp that stings,<br>
He made their prudish venom,<br>
He made their horrid wings.<br>
 <br>
All things sick and cancerous,<br>
All evil great and small,<br>
